column8: Evidence of boring shell species in matrix but no shell present
The scratch/cut marks on some of the shells could be due to cleaning with bamboo skewer see notes in Lab Book
Appears to have been some sorting on site therefore this sample may not be directly comparable to the other totally unsorted samples. MW states no species removed.
Ostrea subcula (Lamy 1925) - some debate could be Neopycnodonte but for the moment Dance classifies as ostrea
One large shell not yet identified Costellaria? Strombus? Crassispira? Or Bullia?
Site bag noted "Complete shells removed on site (Strombus)" therefore may not be possible to use this sample as direct comparison with other totally unsorted samples.

This sample is from the base of the mound and is totally unlike any of the overlaying layers. It is comprised of a very solid matrix in which shells and coral are imbedded. The less solid powdery matrix is of a different colour, redish brown, than the overlaying layers. Prof T O'Connor looked at the sample and it reminded him of calcite deposits, he suggested thin sections would reveal if crystalline or not. Five samples selected for thin sectioning. If not crystalline possibly heavily compressed ash - white and grey in colour. This could prove interesting as the area today is very arid and if calcite in nature may suggest wtter periods in the past.
